So I did this test tonight on an XNA desktop game:

```
private BasicEffect _effect;
private VertexBuffer _vb;
private IndexBuffer _ib;

protected override void Draw(GameTime gameTime)
{
    GraphicsDevice.Clear(Color.CornflowerBlue);

    if (_effect == null)
    {
        _effect = new BasicEffect(GraphicsDevice);

        var vp = GraphicsDevice.Viewport;
        Matrix projection;
        Matrix.CreateOrthographicOffCenter(0, vp.Width, vp.Height, 0, 0, 1, out projection);
        _effect.Projection = projection;
    }

    if (_vb == null)
    {
        _vb = new VertexBuffer(GraphicsDevice, VertexPositionColor.VertexDeclaration, 6, BufferUsage.WriteOnly);
        _vb.SetData( new [] {
            new VertexPositionColor(new Vector3(100, 100, 0), Color.White),
            new VertexPositionColor(new Vector3(200, 100, 0), Color.White),
            new VertexPositionColor(new Vector3(200, 200, 0), Color.White),
            new VertexPositionColor(new Vector3(100, 200, 0), Color.White),
            new VertexPositionColor(new Vector3(100, 100, 0), Color.White),
            new VertexPositionColor(new Vector3(200, 200, 0), Color.White),
        });
        GraphicsDevice.SetVertexBuffer(_vb);
        _vb.Dispose();
    }

    _effect.World = Matrix.Identity;
    _effect.DiffuseColor = Color.Red.ToVector3();
    _effect.CurrentTechnique.Passes[0].Apply();
    GraphicsDevice.DrawPrimitives(PrimitiveType.TriangleList, 0, 2);

    if (_ib == null)
    {
        _ib = new IndexBuffer(GraphicsDevice, IndexElementSize.SixteenBits, 6, BufferUsage.WriteOnly);
        _ib.SetData(new short[] {0, 1, 2, 3, 0, 2});
        GraphicsDevice.Indices = _ib;
        _ib.Dispose();
    }

    _effect.World = Matrix.CreateTranslation(0, 200, 0);
    _effect.DiffuseColor = Color.Green.ToVector3();
    _effect.CurrentTechnique.Passes[0].Apply();
    GraphicsDevice.DrawIndexedPrimitives(PrimitiveType.TriangleList, 0, 0, 4, 0, 2);

    base.Draw(gameTime);
}
```

I did this test fully expecting XNA to throw some helpful exceptions saying the VB and IB were disposed.  I was then going to write this issue saying we need to implement the same checks and exceptions in MonoGame.

BUT

![snip](https://cloud.githubusercontent.com/assets/103522/7861056/71b8980c-0513-11e5-807f-ab89979cc7f0.PNG)

XNA does not throw any exceptions or errors in this case...  In fact it happily draws correctly to the screen... doesn't matter how long it runs.

So I suspect what is happening is a side effect of DirectX being COM based.  COM is reference counted.  So when the VB and IB are set on the GraphicsDevice the underlying `ID3D9GraphicsDevice` is taking a reference to those resources.  When the `Dispose()` is called by the code above it basically does nothing as the resource is still owned by the DX9 device.

Second issue...  although XNA doesn't throw exceptions in this case, should we fix MonoGame to protect against these mistakes?  This behavior is very weird... and tied to the fact that XNA uses DirectX which is COM reference counted.

IMO we shouldn't allow this behavior...  it is hard to replicate across all platforms, it is non-intuitive, and you basically loose control over when your resources are freed.  I think the rule we should follow is simple:

>  You can dispose resources immediately after a draw, but no future draws with that resource should work.

Simple rule... easy to replicate reliably on all platforms.
